message.content:
We start by identifying the key numbers from the financial statements.

─────────────────────────────  
1. Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio  
• From the cash‐flow statement, “Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities” = –6,856,840.58  
• From the balance sheet, “Total Current Liabilities” = 1,601,835.08  
  Ratio = (–6,856,840.58) ÷ 1,601,835.08 ≈ –4.28  

─────────────────────────────  
2. Debt to Equity Ratio  
• Total Liabilities are not separately given besides current liabilities. (There are no long‑term liabilities provided.)  
• Therefore Total Liabilities = Total Assets – Total Owner’s Equity =  
  12,566,098.56 – 10,964,263.48 = 1,601,835.08  
• Total Owner’s Equity (end) = 10,964,263.48  
  Debt to Equity = 1,601,835.08 ÷ 10,964,263.48 ≈ 0.15  

─────────────────────────────  
3. Total Asset Turnover Ratio  
• From the income statement, “Total Revenue” = 6,836,701.10  
• From the balance sheet, ending “Total Assets” = 12,566,098.56  
  Ratio = 6,836,701.10 ÷ 12,566,098.56 ≈ 0.54  

─────────────────────────────  
4. Quick Ratio  
Quick assets include Cash (on hand and bank), Accounts Receivable, and Interest Receivable.  
• Cash on Hand = 376,598.62  
• Bank Deposits = 100,482.62  
• Accounts Receivable = 3,098,023.69  
• Interest Receivable = 5,155.34  
  Sum of quick assets = 376,598.62 + 100,482.62 + 3,098,023.69 + 5,155.34  
                   ≈ 3,580,260.27  
• Total Current Liabilities = 1,601,835.08  
  Quick Ratio = 3,580,260.27 ÷ 1,601,835.08 ≈ 2.23  

─────────────────────────────  
5. Operating Cash Flow Ratio  
Often defined the same as the operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio. Therefore, it is also  
  –6,856,840.58 ÷ 1,601,835.08 ≈ –4.28  

─────────────────────────────  
6. Return on Equity (ROE)  
Here we use the net profit and the average owner’s equity.  
• Net Profit (from income statement) = –2,035,736.52  
• Beginning Owner’s Equity (from balance sheet – on 2023‑12‑31) = 13,000,000.00  
• Ending Owner’s Equity = 10,964,263.48  
  Average Owner’s Equity = (13,000,000.00 + 10,964,263.48) ÷ 2  
                   ≈ 11,982,131.74  
  ROE = (–2,035,736.52) ÷ 11,982,131.74 ≈ –0.17 or –17.00%  

─────────────────────────────  
7. Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio  
We use the revenue and the average accounts receivable.  
• Beginning Accounts Receivable = 0.00 (per the balance sheet)  
• Ending Accounts Receivable = 3,098,023.69  
  Average Accounts Receivable = (0 + 3,098,023.69) ÷ 2 = 1,549,011.85  
• Total Revenue = 6,836,701.10  
  Ratio = 6,836,701.10 ÷ 1,549,011.85 ≈ 4.41  

─────────────────────────────  
Now, we present the final answers in the required JSON format.

{
  "solution": {
    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-4.28",
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.15",
    "Total Asset Turnover Ratio": "0.54",
    "Quick Ratio": "2.23",
    "Operating Cash Flow Ratio": "-4.28",
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "-17.00%",
    "Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio": "4.41"
  }
}
